import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data['date'] = pd.to_datetime(data['date'], errors='coerce')
    data = data[pd.notna(data['date'])]
    
    fig, ax = plt.subplots()
    data.boxplot(column='rate', by='state', ax=ax)
    ax.set_title('What is the distribution of rate across all states?')
    ax.set_xlabel('State')
    ax.set_ylabel('Rate')
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)
    plt.suptitle('')
    plt.legend(title='States', loc='upper right')
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data['date'] = pd.to_datetime(data['date'], errors='coerce')
    data = data[pd.notna(data['date'])]
    
    max_rate_state = data.loc[data['rate'].idxmax()]['state']
    max_rate = data['rate'].max()

    data_grouped = data.groupby('state')['rate'].mean().reset_index()
    data_grouped = data_grouped.sort_values('rate', ascending=False)

    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
    plt.bar(data_grouped['state'], data_grouped['rate'], color='b', alpha=0.7)
    plt.axhline(y=max_rate, color='r', linestyle='--', label=f'Highest Rate: {max_rate:.2f}')
    plt.xlabel('State')
    plt.ylabel('Rate')
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)
    plt.title('Which state has the highest rate?', wrap=True)
    plt.legend()
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)
